Extremes.
I am busted; I am busted;
Not a dollar to my name;
And with my forlorn condition,
Comes a sense of want and shame.
I am busted; nearly busted;
Joy for me has sadly flown;
For to give me cheer and comfort,
Fifty cents I do not own.
I am busted; badly busted;
Light of heart I cannot be;
For in all the tide of quarters,
Not a quarter comes to me.

I am busted; really busted;
And I feel such keen destress;
For among my other trifles,
Not a dime do I possess.
I am busted; sadly busted;
And it preys upon my mind;
For in all my many pockets,
Not a nickel do I find.
I am busted; more than busted;
And I cannot be content;
For, indeed, if I must say it - 
I have not a single cent!
E.A. Barnes.

X
Face to Face.
Face to face, with ancient laws;
Face to face, with customs old;
The master came, a humble man,
Now teaching to unfold.
Face to face, with unbelief;
Face to face, with scorn and pride;
The Savior walked His lonely way,
With foes on every side.
Face to face, with want and sin;
Face to face, with bitter grief;
The Master gave, as none could give,
The balm of sweet relief.

Face to face with cross and thorn;
Face to face, with mortal pain;
The Savior died and by His death,
The soul shall live again.
E.A. Barnes.

Good night, My love.
Sweet are the moments, love,
I spend with thee;
Sweet in the rapture, love,
They bring to me.
Here, at this rustic seat;
Here, where we often meet;
Kiss me, goodnight, my love,
Kiss me, goodnight,
Goodnight, my love.
